# AWS secure HA Two-Tier Architecture (Terraform)

Architecture includes:
- VPC with public and private subnets
- Application Load Balancer
- Auto Scaling Group (EC2 web/app servers)
- Multi-AZ RDS (MySQL) database
- Secure access via Systems Manager (SSM)
- Secure access via IAM AUTH for DB
- NAT Gateway for outbound internet
- VPC Interface Endpoints for SSM components
- IAM roles and security groups

# Architecture Diagram
![Architecture](./secure_two-tier_architecture.png)

This deployment provides:

1. Web Tier (Auto Scaling Group)**  
   - EC2 instances in private subnets  
   - Placed behind an Application Load Balancer  
   - Automatically scales based on configured capacity

2. Database Tier (RDS)**  
   - MySQL instance with Multi-AZ replication
   - Encrypted storage
   - Private subnet group, no public access
   - MySQL DB login via sts token(IAM DB AUTH)

3. Security Best Practices**  
   - EC2 has no public IPs  
   - SSM for management (no SSH exposed)
   - Proper security group scopes between ALB, EC2, and RDS

4. Networking**  
   - Public subnets host ALB and NAT Gateway  
   - Private subnets host EC2 and RDS
   - Public-to-private routing via NAT

# Deployment Steps

1. Configure AWS Credentials
Set up your AWS credentials locally:

# export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="xxxx"
# export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY="xxxx"
# export AWS_DEFAULT_REGION="ap-northeast-1"

2. Initialize terraform
# terraform init

3. validate configuration
# terraform validate 

3. Review Plan
# terraform plan

3. Apply Planned infra
# terraform apply

After successful apply:
Check ALB DNS in the AWS console and open it in browser
Ensure EC2 instances are running in private subnets
Confirm ASG has 2+ instances across 2 AZs
In RDS, verify Multi-AZ is enabled
EC2 doesn’t have public IP — SSH disabled — use SSM

Connect to Ec2
login to Ec2 instance from local bash with instance-id
# aws ssm start-session --target i-xxxxxxxxxxx

Connect to RDS (IAM Auth)
login to Ec2 instance
check mysql version as to be 8.0
# mysql --version

install ssl-ca pem file.
# sudo curl -O https://truststore.pki.rds.amazonaws.com/global/global-bundle.pem

db_password = "123456789"
For initial login, use password configured to db_password.
# Eg;
mysql -h terraform-2026030213565098330000000c.c122oymqotpa.ap-northeast-1.rds.amazonaws.com \
-P 3306 \
-u master_db_user \
--ssl-mode=VERIFY_CA \
--ssl-ca=global-bundle.pem \
-p”123456789” \
no_cost_db

after successfull initial login, 
update db_user to use AWSAuthenticationPlugin instead of mysql_native_password.
# Eg;
mysql> ALTER USER 'master_db_user'@'%' IDENTIFIED WITH AWSAuthenticationPlugin AS 'RDS';
mysql> GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON no_cost_db.* TO 'master_db_user'@'%';
mysql> FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

Logout mysql, reconnect DB using IAM token.
# Eg;
mysql -h terraform-2026030213565098330000000c.c122oymqotpa.ap-northeast-1.rds.amazonaws.com \
-P 3306 \
-u master_db_user \
--ssl-mode=VERIFY_CA \
--ssl-ca=global-bundle.pem \
-p"$(aws rds generate-db-auth-token \
--hostname terraform-2026030213565098330000000c.c122oymqotpa.ap-northeast-1.rds.amazonaws.com \
--port 3306 \
--username master_db_user \
--region ap-northeast-1)" \
no_cost_db


